      "content": "iwoca launches support for Yorkshire’s female business owners - iwoca            \n\n[![iwoca logo in red coral](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/6480aa50abfc4038a33d5763_iwoca-coral-logo.svg)](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/)\n\n[\n\nBusiness Loans\n\n](/small-business-loans)\n\niwocaPay\n\n[iwocaPay](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/iwocapay-sellers)[Integrations](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/iwocapay-integrations)\n\n[\n\nResources\n\n](/resources)\n\nAbout\n\n[About us](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/about-us)[Careers](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/careers)[Inside iwoca](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/inside-iwoca)[Press and news](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/news)[Sustainability](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/esg)[Customer stories](/customer-stories)[SME Expert Index](/research)[SME impact report](/sme-impact-report)\n\n[\n\nLog in\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/696fbd1ab654c38c93609670_Lock-icon.svg)](/login/)[\n\nApply now\n\n\n\n\n\n](/apply/new)\n\n[My Account](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/my_account/)\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/696fbd1a4666e54e5bb3e10f_icon-phone-colour.svg)\n\nOpen Mon-Fri 9-6pm\n\n[020 3778 0274](tel:+442037780274)\n\nMenu\n\nBusiness Loans\n\n[Business Loans](/small-business-loans)\n\niwocapay\n\n[iwocaPay](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/iwocapay-sellers)[Integrations](/iwocapay-integrations)\n\nResources\n\n[Resources](/resources)\n\nAbout\n\n[About us](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/about-us)[Careers](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/careers)[Inside iwoca](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/inside-iwoca)[Press and news](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/news)[Sustainability](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/esg)[Customer stories](/customer-stories)[SME Expert Index](/research)[SME impact report](/sme-impact-report)\n\n# iwoca launches support for Yorkshire’s female business owners\n\nNews\n\n5\n\nmin read\n\n## iwoca launches support for Yorkshire’s female business owners\n\nJuly 28, 2021\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/63c54d1794eb3950c0114fc4_Wholeteam__1_.jpeg)\n\n![red wedge](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63b6efc7e1719bbae77b80b3_Wedge.svg)\n\n[Home](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/)\n\n[News](/news)\n\n[iwoca launches support for Yorkshire’s female business owners](/news/yorkshire-female-businesses)\n\n![grey wedge](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63b6eab8e70adc1a7dfbfdb8_Wedge.svg)\n\n![yellow dot](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63b6ecd52568c01c36ee79f6_Group%2021580.svg)\n\n![grey line with green square](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/6399b356131a1e569254e611_finance-line-square.svg)\n\n![blue square](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63b6ee6e6a738f61c89358e1_Rectangle%202607.svg)\n\n*   We've set up a new regional forum for female business owners in Yorkshire, providing workshop sessions from industry leaders and partners.\n*   Slow progress has been made in increasing the number of female-led businesses in the UK, rising by just one percentage point in the past decade.\n*   Our analysis suggests female workers in Yorkshire have been more affected by the pandemic than many other regions.\n*   Our survey reveals at the end of 2020, 21% of female-owned businesses were not trading compared to 13% of male-owned firms, highlighting the need for more support to aid post-pandemic recovery.\n\nWe've launched a new support initiative for women business owners in Yorkshire as local data suggests female workers in the region have been more affected by the pandemic than many other parts of the UK.\n\nWe've lent close to £80 million to small and micro businesses in Yorkshire since we launched in 2012 (av. loan size between £12,000 - £15,000), but the vast majority of these applications have been from male business owners. As part of an effort to support more female entrepreneurs, we're announcing a new initiative specifically for women-led small businesses in the Yorkshire & Humber region. This also comes after we were recently crowned “Lender of the Year\" and “Innovative Product of the Year\" at the [Yorkshire Financial Awards](http://yorkshirefinancialawards.co.uk/yorkshire-financial-awards-2021-meet-the-winners/).\n\nWe're launching a new regional network hub with local founding members Rebecca Lockwood, a coach for female entrepreneurs, and her sister Cathy Cockin, owner of an all-female electrician business - Little Miss Electrical. The forum will be a place for female business owners in the region to connect, share experiences and get access to resources and information from partner companies as well as experts at iwoca.\n\nWe've chosen to launch the first regional forum in Yorkshire following the opening of our office in Leeds last year. We'll launch with a series of expert webinars, including confirmed guest speakers from the charity [Mental Health UK](https://mentalhealth-uk.org/) to give advice on coping with stress and anxiety, and [Pink Pig Financials](https://pinkpigfinancials.co.uk/) accountancy firm to give advice on managing business finances. Further workshop sessions along with regional funding updates will be announced throughout the year.\n\nOur analysis suggests female workers in Yorkshire have been more affected by the pandemic than many other regions. ONS data reveals that the ‘Accommodation & Food’ and ‘Arts & Entertainment’ sectors saw the largest drop in output last year, with both these sectors employing more women than men. Yorkshire has the second largest proportion of businesses in these sectors out of all English regions, suggesting women in the area are most at risk of being hit hard by the aftershocks of the pandemic.\n\n**Yorkshire business owner, Rebecca Lockwood – owner of a** [**female entrepreneur training consultancy**](https://rebeccalockwood.org.uk/)  **– said:** “The pandemic has been tough – I teach women how to look after their mental health and mindset, but when the first lockdown began I wasn’t listening to my own advice and it was stressful and scary. My business is all about helping women fulfil their potential and have the confidence to be the best entrepreneurs possible. All business owners need support for the varied and acute stresses that come in tow, but I think in particular female business owners struggle more with the mindset side of things.\n\n“We put so much pressure on ourselves to be successful and often experience issues with things like imposter syndrome, and having the confidence to take bigger risks. I started another business before this, but it failed because of a lack of self belief. That's why I'm so passionate about what I do now – because I went through it myself.”\n\n![Yorkshire business owner, Rebecca Lockwood – owner of a female entrepreneur training consultancy | iwoca](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/63d016e9c190425646261700_RL311018-5__2_.jpeg)\n\n_Yorkshire business owner, Rebecca Lockwood – owner of a female entrepreneur training consultancy_\n\n## Need to champion female business owners across the UK\n\nThe announcement comes as analysis of government data reveals that little progress has been made in increasing the number of female-led businesses in the UK, rising by just one percentage point in the past decade. In 2010, the proportion of female-led businesses sat at 14%, and in 2019 it increased to just 15%.\n\nIn addition, a recent survey of small business owners by iwoca highlighted that female-owned businesses have been hit harder by the Covid-19 crisis. At the end of 2020, 21% of female-owned businesses were not trading, compared to just 13% of male-owned small businesses. Women were also more likely to feel worried about the future of their businesses. The same survey revealed 47% of female business owners are concerned about having to close their business in 2021, compared to 35% of men.\n\n<div class=\"smallQuote\">I sometimes turn up to jobs where people assume the electrician is a man who will appear from somewhere behind me, or think that I’m the receptionist</div>\n\n**Cathy Cockin, owner of** [**Little Miss Electrical**](https://littlemisselectrical.co.uk/) **– an all-female electrician business in Halifax, West Yorkshire (sister of Rebecca Lockwood) – added:** “I followed in my big sister's entrepreneurial footsteps, and took the leap to starting my own business. It’s been a roller coaster with some of the best days alongside some of the most challenging. From HR, to recruitment to payroll, there are just so many different things you have to learn when setting up your business, most of which are not part of your immediate skill set.\n\n“We’re an all-female team of electrical contractors, mainly doing domestic work and looking after a lot of rental properties. A large amount of our work comes from local people who knew me from school or growing up. Even though the business has been trading for four years, I sometimes turn up to jobs where people assume the electrician is a man who will appear from somewhere behind me, or think that I’m the receptionist. I’m proud that Little Miss Electrical is challenging these ideals on a daily basis.”\n\n![Cathy Cockin, owner of Little Miss Electrical (sister of Rebecca Lockwood)](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/63d016e9c190425b672616ff_Cathy_in_front_of_van.jpeg)\n\n_Yorkshire business owner, Cathy Cockin – owner of Little Miss Electrical (sister of Rebecca Lockwood)_\n\n**Seema Desai, Chief Operating Officer at iwoca:** “We feel proud to be able to give female business owners in Yorkshire the support they need during this time. Last year, we opened our office in Leeds, which alongside our recent funding pledge of £220 million to businesses across the North by 2023, demonstrates our commitment and desire to help local business owners realise their ideas and get access to finance to help them grow.\n\n“Female business owners can play a crucial role in the UK’s economic recovery. We hope initiatives like this provide the further support needed to allow female-owned businesses to thrive in the years ahead.”\n\n## Coronavirus Business Interruption Loan Scheme (CBILS)\n\niwoca played an important role in supporting small businesses through the pandemic by lending £250 million through the [Coronavirus Business Interruption Loans Scheme (CBILS)](https://www.iwoca.co.uk/cbils) and will continue to lend to businesses across the UK until the scheme closes.\n\n_Full analysis of research used is available on request._\n\n{{flexi-loan=\"/components\"}}\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/63c542a4f8fb9d34265b0746_Charlotte_Emms.webp)\n\nWords by\n\n[\n\nCharlotte Emms\n\n](/author/charlotte-emms)\n\nCharlotte was a UK PR Manager at iwoca. She's been sharing news and insights about the finance industry for over four years.\n\nArticle updated on:\n\nJuly 28, 2021\n\n[![file attached icon in blue](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63bd89d81127badb6a6a13dc_link-icon.svg)](#)[![linkedin icon](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63bd89d70c22b0e694e5cb0a_linkedin-icon.svg)](#)[![twitter blue logo](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63bd89d8205e8288af9f5e85_twitter-icon.svg)](#)[![facebook icon](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/63bd89d7c8163fa73542df49_facebook-icon.svg)](#)\n\n### Get started\n\n*   Borrow up to £1,000,000\n*   Repay early with no fees\n*   From 1 day to 24 months\n*   Applying won't affect your credit score\n\n[\n\nApply now\n\n\n\n\n\n](/apply/new)\n\n![red line and yellow circle](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/62b040bf442187a12361b14f/6399b200b6439f01847c32b0_yellow-circle-red-line.svg)\n\n## Related Articles\n\n[\n\nView all\n\n\n\n\n\n](/news)\n\n[\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/69ca89ab4d8e82555bd18442_photo-1700049542324-56d80819a4ea.avif)\n\n### Full steam ahead: Darlington named top British town to work for an SME\n\nDarlington is ranked the best town or city to work for a small business in Britain, toppling last year’s leader Newcastle, according to new research released today by iwoca, one of Europe’s largest SME lenders.\n\nApril 1, 2026\n\n•\n\n2\n\nmin read\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n](/news/darlington-named-top-british-town-to-work-for-an-sme)\n\n[\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/69b815f7eeeda382c8f9f6d9_CreditCompass_press.png)\n\n### iwoca launches Credit Compass to help millions of SMEs understand and improve their business credit score\n\nNew research from iwoca, one of Europe’s leading SME lenders, reveals that a significant proportion of UK SMEs lack a clear understanding of their own financial health - a gap that could put their success at risk. \n\nMarch 16, 2026\n\n•\n\n2\n\nmin read\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n](/news/iwoca-launches-credit-compass-to-help-of-smes)\n\n[\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/670fa144a4a8f8579ee7b8e7_sme1.avif)\n\n### Business cost concerns hit record high as SMEs brace for April tax rises, finance brokers say\n\nMore than half (58%) of finance brokers cite increased running costs as small business owners' biggest concern, according to iwoca's latest SME Expert Index. \n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/670e3c9f46f570976177ef42_farah.webp)\n\nFarah Sisalem\n\nFebruary 19, 2026\n\n•\n\n2\n\nmin read\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n](/news/business-cost-concerns-hit-record-high)\n\n## Other finance related topics\n\nLorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.\n\n[View all](#)\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/63441419ee90330b7aa81150/6697ea57970b339a147ac96b_businessownerfemale.webp)\n\nAlternative business funding\n\n### How to use payroll loans for small businesses\n\n![](https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/plugins/Basic/assets/placeholder.60f9b1840c