perty_directory/detail/henry-boot-developments \"View Profile for HBD\"), Sheffield\n        *   [Town Centre Securities PLC](/property_directory/detail/business-2445 \"View Profile for Town Centre Securities PLC\"), Leeds\n        *   [Cripps](/property_directory/detail/business-4930 \"View Profile for Cripps\"), Tunbridge Wells\n        \n        [\n        \n        #### Search Property Directory\n        \n        ](/property_directory)\n        \n        *   [Muckle LLP](/property_directory/detail/business-4355 \"View Profile for Muckle LLP\"), Newcastle\n        *   [Harworth Group](/property_directory/detail/business-4200 \"View Profile for Harworth Group\"), Rotherham\n        *   [Mincoffs Solicitors](/property_directory/detail/business-426 \"View Profile for Mincoffs Solicitors\"), Newcastle upon Tyne\n        *   [Towngate plc](/property_directory/detail/business-2718 \"View Profile for Towngate plc\"), Brighouse\n        \n        [\n        \n        #### Add your business profile to our Property Directory\n        \n        ](/property_directory#add-your-company)\n        \n    \n\n*   [Home](/)\n*   [News](/news)\n*   [Yorkshire](/news/yorkshire)\n\n[Advertisement](/advertising)\n\n[Yorkshire](/yorkshire)\n\n# Yorkshire and the Humber falls down UK rankings in PwC’s Women in Work Index - “meaningful progress on pay equality, but deteriorating performance across most other measures”\n\n[![Stephen Farrell](https://www.insidermedia.com/images/avatars/uploads/avatar_59_2.jpg)](/news/author/stephen-farrell)\n\n[By Stephen Farrell](/news/author/stephen-farrell)\n\n6 Mar 2026, 06:00\n\n  \nShare\n\nCopy link [Email](/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection# \"Share via email\")\n\n[LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insidermedia.com%2Fnews%2Fyorkshire%2Fyorkshire-and-the-humber-falls-down-uk-rankings-in-pwcs-women-in-work-index-meaningful-progress-on-pay-equality-but-deteriorating-performance-across-most-other-measures \"Share on LinkedIn\") [X / Twitter](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insidermedia.com%2Fnews%2Fyorkshire%2Fyorkshire-and-the-humber-falls-down-uk-rankings-in-pwcs-women-in-work-index-meaningful-progress-on-pay-equality-but-deteriorating-performance-across-most-other-measures&text=Yorkshire%20and%20the%20Humber%20falls%20down%20UK%20rankings%20in%20PwC%27s%20Women%20in%20Work%20Index%20-%20%22meaningful%20progress%20on%20pay%20equality%2C%20but%20deteriorating%20performance%20across%20most%20other%20measures%22 \"Share on X/Twitter\") [Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insidermedia.com%2Fnews%2Fyorkshire%2Fyorkshire-and-the-humber-falls-down-uk-rankings-in-pwcs-women-in-work-index-meaningful-progress-on-pay-equality-but-deteriorating-performance-across-most-other-measures \"Share on Facebook\") [WhatsApp](https://wa.me/?text=Yorkshire%20and%20the%20Humber%20falls%20down%20UK%20rankings%20in%20PwC%27s%20Women%20in%20Work%20Index%20-%20%22meaningful%20progress%20on%20pay%20equality%2C%20but%20deteriorating%20performance%20across%20most%20other%20measures%22%0Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fwww.insidermedia.com%2Fnews%2Fyorkshire%2Fyorkshire-and-the-humber-falls-down-uk-rankings-in-pwcs-women-in-work-index-meaningful-progress-on-pay-equality-but-deteriorating-performance-across-most-other-measures \"Share on WhatsApp\")\n\n[Add us on Google](https://www.google.com/preferences/source?q=insidermedia.com \"Add Insider as a preferred source on Google\")\n\n![Yorkshire and the Humber falls down UK rankings in PwC’s Women in Work Index - “meaningful progress on pay equality, but deteriorating performance across most other measures”](/uploads/news/images/PwC_Katie_Johnston.jpg)\n\nKatie Johnston, partner based in PwC's Leeds office (image credit: PwC)\n\nYorkshire and the Humber has fallen down the UK rankings of PwC's Women in Work Index 2026, with progress on pay equality but a deteriorating performance in most other areas.\n\nPwC's 2026 Index, now in its 15th year, tracks the progress of women in the workplace across the UK regions and 33 OECD countries using five indicators covering pay, participation, unemployment and full-time employment for women.\n\nYorkshire and the Humber experienced a two‑place drop in the rankings to 11th place out of 12 UK regions, and a 0.5‑point decline in its overall Index score.\n\nIt now ranks below the UK regional average in four out of five key indicators.\n\nPwC said one of the most concerning trends was the 2 percentage point fall in female labour force participation, with Yorkshire and the Humber dropping four places on this indicator and ranking second lowest nationally. This decline stands out against a backdrop where several other regions recorded improvements in women's participation in the workforce. \n\nHowever, the data also pointed to an area of progress. Yorkshire and the Humber recorded a 2.6 percentage point reduction in the gender pay gap, the second largest improvement of any UK region, and gained two places in the pay gap rankings as a result.\n\nKatie Johnston, partner based in PwC's Leeds office, said: \"The findings paint a mixed picture for our region: meaningful progress on pay equality, but deteriorating performance across most other measures, including overall participation. The results underline the need for sustained focus on supporting women's access to work and progression, alongside continued efforts to close the gender pay gap. \n\n\"Too many young women in Yorkshire and the Humber are failing to connect to the economy at the point where it matters most. When that disengagement happens early, the effects compound - lower lifetime earnings, weaker attachment to the labour market, and a higher risk of long‑term inactivity. This isn't just about a difficult year in the data. It's about whether we allow disadvantage to become embedded for the next thirty years, or whether we act now to strengthen pathways into work, skills and progression.\"\n\nNationally, while the UK's overall Index score increased marginally (+0.16 points), the climb in the rankings was mostly due to declines in other countries' performance. If the UK's improvement had matched Australia's since 2020, it would have placed fourth in the Index rankings rather than 17th.\n\nPwC's latest analysis suggested that the UK could unlock major economic gains by reducing the number of young women who are not in education, employment or training (NEET). \n\nGermany and the Netherlands have some of the lowest NEET rates in Europe. Bringing female NEET rates in line with Germany could add £5bn UK GDP, while matching the Netherlands could deliver up to £11bn. Even returning to the UK's 2021 level would generate a further £3bn. \n\n[Advertisement](/advertising)\n\n## Missing important news updates?\n\n       \n\nSign up to our newsletter \n\n#### Select your newsletter(s)\n\n*   Yorkshire Mon - Fri\n*   South Yorkshire Wed\n*   Hull & Humber Mon\n*   Insider Weekend Sat, Sun\n\n#### Professional information\n\nFirst Name \\* \n\nSurname \\* \n\nPosition Select... Accountant Analyst Banker Business Development Manager Chief Executive Chairman Consultant Company Secretary Director Executive Financial Director General Manager HR Manager IT Manager Managing Director Manager Marketing Director Marketing Manager Managing Partner Officer Owner Partner Professional Proprietor Sales Director Sales Manager Solicitor Senior Partner Other - please specify\n\nIf other please specify \\* \n\nCompany Name \n\nSector Select... Accountants Advertising Agriculture, fishing & forestry Architects Asset-based lending Auctions Banking Business and management consultancy Central government Charity, third sector Construction: Civil engineering Construction: Commercial property Corporate finance advisers Education: Further education & training Education: Higher education Education: Schools Electricity, gas, water and renewables Healthcare Hotels and conference centres Industrial cl